comments: The disability surveys were often worded as if the participant only had one disability. As I have several I answered with regard to all of my disabilities. For instance my disabilities as a whole limit my opportunities for success, even though it is one particular disability that does so. Also some of my disabilities I have had since birth, and others I have only more recently acquired. Wording of questions is important, if you care about nuance. If you don't care about the difference between chronic health problems versus shorter term health problems then your questions were fine. An example would be: I used to have severe anemia and I developed it when participating in an online graduate degree. Since my anemia was so bad that I couldn't type correctly (due to tremors in my hands) I had to suspend my graduate program, therefore my anemia greatly impacted my life. However I also have chronic migraines and I have gotten so used to managing those that I can do fine when having a migraine during school.

I'm not sure if this helps you, but I sincerely hope that it is recognized that many millennial's are experiencing multi-layered problems that fully enhance their perspectives of life, their abilities, and their understanding of the American Dream.

transgres: I talked about the experience with my therapist
comments:
Some of the answers for me were difficult because I was unsure if I had the same definition of what was being asked. For example, the questions about the American dream were hard for me. I know what the idealistic notion of it is, which Google defines as, "the ideal that every US citizen should have an equal opportunity to achieve success and prosperity through hard work, determination, and initiative." I also believe, however, that the "American dream" is a whole lot harder to define than this. I am not sure if I have my own working definition and understanding of what it means to me yet, so I was not sure how to best answer the question. Instead of saying that I totally agree (assuming definition given by Google) or entirely unsure (assuming my own incomplete definition), I chose the 'somewhat agree' option. Also, I realize that the sheer level of my physical discomforts/ailments indicate a sensitivity to experiencing psychosomatic symptoms; however, I do have a chronic heart condition that induces probably at least half of those which I indicated. 

On another note, I think you should change your question about the marriage status of biological parents. It was difficult to figure out a correct category as a person who has already experienced the death of a parent (and whose other parent is remarried). 

I'm sure there were other things I wanted to clarify, but I can't remember them right now.

Thank you. I hope you get lots of participation to help with this project.
